Berkshire’s class A shares on Monday crossed $300,000 for the first time.
The stock is up more than 1 percent in recent trading and nearly 11 percent since mid-November. The stock has rallied as optimism for the enactment of the Republican tax overhaul has grown. Berkshire’s focus on the United States means the company stands to be a big winner from the bill’s passage, 
The move above $300,000
“Mr. Buffett put in his first order to buy 2,000 shares with Wall Street broker Tweedy, Browne and Reilly back on Dec. 12, 1962. He paid $7.50 a share for his initial stake. That’s an increase of roughly four million percent.”
Mr. Buffett took control of Berkshire in 1965 and built the struggling textile company into a conglomerate. Along the way, the stock steadily climbed. It ”pierced the $1,000 level in 1983, passed $10,000 in 1992 and hit $100,000 for the first time in 2006. It first touched $250,000 intraday 
Mr. Buffett currently owns 17 percent of the company, worth about $85 billion.
